03167nam a2200457 i 6784290CaPaEBR20141116163904.0m    eo  d        cr cn |||m|||a141116s2015    nyu    foab   001 0 eng d  a9781606495315qe-book  z9781606495308qpaperback  aexclude  aCaBNVSLbengerdacCaBNVSLdCaBNVSLdAEU 4aHB172.5b.S626 201504a339223  aInternet AccessbAEU1 aSnarr, Hal W.,eauthor.10aLearning macroeconomic principles using MAPLE /cHal W. Snarr.  aFirst edition. 1aNew York, New York (222 East 46th Street, New York, NY 10017) :bBusiness Expert Press,c2015.  a1 online resource (xii, 137 pages)  atext2rdacontent  acomputer2rdamedia  aonline resource2rdacarrier1 aEconomics collection,x2163-7628  aPart of: 2014 digital library.  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 131-134) and index.0 aHow to Use MAPLE -- Foundations of macroeconomics -- Aggregate expenditure -- The aggregate market model -- Fiscal policy -- Monetary policy -- What have we learned?  aAccess restricted to authorized users and institutions.3 aEconomics has been dubbed the "dismal science" since Thomas Carlyle coined the phrase in 1849. The 2008 presidential candidate who said, "Economics is something that I've really never understood," probably sides with this view. So, why is economics so dismal to so many? Is it because it has become too mathematical? Is it because traditional textbooks fail to connect topics and models in a concise, cohesive, and meaningful way? Is it because the computer simulations that are used to teach economic principles "stifle students' imagination, contribute to a dependent learning style, and fail to stimulate interest in the subject matter" (Wetzstein 1988)? Or, is it because economists from different schools of economic thought rarely agree on anything? This book uses MAPLE and the simulation models that I developed in Learning Basic Macroeconomics (2014) to make teaching or learning economics not so dismal. MAPLE is ideally suited for this because it allows users to assemble and systematically combine the various models that form the aggregate market model, frees users from doing tedious calculations and algebraic manipulations, and is as easy to use as Microsoft Word. Building and analyzing the macroeconomic model using MAPLE is a fun way to learn the dismal science.  aTitle from PDF title page (viewed on November 16, 2014).  a4400aMaple (Computer file) 0aMacroeconomicsxComputer simulation. 0aEconomics collection.x2163-7628403University of Alberta Accessuhttp://site.ebrary.com/lib/ualbertagep/Doc?id=10978737  hUAINzEBRARYBEP  aInternet AccesswLCc1i6784290-1001lINTERNETmUAINTERNETrYsYtE-RESOURCEu1/16/2015xE-BOOKzEBRARYBEP01ahttp://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/no2016019301